betterquesting:10.desc:8: Does what is sounds like. It's an implosion compressor that doesn't use explosives. Although you can build it at UV, it requires UHV power to run.

Were you feeling slow? Tired of jumping for 1 block spaces? Perhaps not bulky enough?

The Dark Steel armor and tools are now available. Be sure to check the upgrades, they are craftables and do not require xp investment.

Some recipes use Molds, a non consumed item to help shape materials into different forms.
Make a ball mold.

The chanced boost multiplied by the base chanced output chance of the recipe is the base chance in the large machine. The boost multiplied by the chance per tier of the recipe is the chance per tier in the large machine.
<PLACEHOLDER>
No Description
HV age here we go!
This machine turns dusts into gems, and has some other uses as well.

Congratulations, you have reached the first tier of progression: Steam! Steam machines are slow, need pipe connection, don't handle auto-output. But one must start somewhere.

Steam machines (not boilers!) have an exhaust vent, represented by a gray square on their backside by default. This vent can be moved using a wrench, but must remain unblocked. After every recipe, steam particles will be exhausted and hurt entities unfortunate enough to be standing there (Yes, that's a way players die in Gregtech...). Keep the exhaust vent unblocked, or the machine stop operating.


Steam age is sped up in this modpack as opposed to standard Gregtech, less grind more joy!

Reminder: Wrenches are the best tool to break GT machines!
HV tier materials and components.
Welcome to <Placeholder: Gregicality Community Modpack>

One of the main components of the primitive processor is Red Alloy. It is an alloy of Redstone and Copper, and can be made in your Steam Alloy Smelter.

Remember that the way to obtain clean dusts is by throwing the impure dusts in a cauldron filled with water.

Just Enough Items will be your best friend in this journey. Learning how to use it will be crucial to help you out understand the ins and outs of the modpack.

Bookmark items regularly (default key 'A') so you don't have to remember what you needed to craft, and won't have to type the names over and over.

Most of the items have multiple recipes! Don't stop at the first apparent recipe and think it's unobtainable. Sometimes a material is only available from tiny dusts, sometimes it's available from a fluid solution. It takes some practice.

You might realize that your inventory will quickly be filled up with junk, cobblestone, ores, everything. How can you fix this? A Satchel of course! In this modpack instead of normal Thermal ones, there are tiered satchels, from normal leather, into emerald.


§7§8First Satchel §f(Tier 1): 9 Slots

§8§7Iron satchel §f(Tier 2): 18 Slots

§eGold satchel §f(Tier 3): 27 Slots

§3§9Diamond satchel §f(Tier 4): 36 Slots

§aEmerald satchel §f(Tier 5): 45 Slots


Along with the original size, you are able to enchant satchels with the Holding enchants, with every Holding level 9 Slots are added.

This machine uses Hyper Fuel to produce EVEN MORE power than the Large Naquadah Reactor. If helium plasma is used in addition to hyper fuel, it will consume 2x the fuel with the same duration, but the power output is multiplied by 3.

Hot ingots are hot! They burn! How convenient that would be if something was automatically putting transferring them to your freshly made Vacuum Freezer. Well, we have that for you.

The Ore Dictionary filter lets you type an oredict and add a wildcard to automatically filter all the predicates. No need to specify items.

Here's a list of some the useful oredicts:

§5ingotHot*§r for hot ingots to send to your Vacuum Freezer

§5dustRegular*§r for plain clean dusts, it can help with ore processing

§5depletedFuel*§r for nuclear depleted fuels (not helpful right now, but will come handy)
Used in the Hyper Reactor I.

Smelting down 128 kanthal ingots took an eternity!! And now you have 2 sets of coils... So why not make a second EBF?? What a deal! As you progress further, you will want to make more and more EBFs.


In Gregicality, they are also used for alternate ore processing.

Epoxy will be your next polymer for circuit boards. All future boards will also require Epoxy as a base.

Making it will be the hardest challenge yet in terms of chemistry complexity. Similarly to Polyethylene, you have 2 main routes, including oil or excluding it. We will guide you through both, but this will be the last time. If you hate submitting fluids, rejoice!

Note that we purposely ignore the Naphtha recipe as it is very lossy and not intended for mass production.
Stellar Containment Casings are used in the Stellar Forge.

To power steam machines, you need steam of course!

There are different ways to produce steam, there is the Lava Boiler, the Solar Boiler, and the Large Boilers. The latter being a little bit out of reach for now. We recommend you start with the Small Steam Coal Boiler, the most standard and steadiest. It is powered by furnace fuels and is extremely fuel efficient.

Boilers take some time to heat up, and once hot enough they will consume water and automatically output steam into connected pipes/machines. Be careful though, boilers can §4explode§0§r, though the one condition for it to happen it when they are already hot, have no water and you add some water. Keeping them filled permanently with water is completely safe, and recommended.

The EBF requires no less than 120eu/t to operate. You will need to supply 4 Amps of LV to reach that power.

This is done either by either having 2 LV Energy hatches, or the Gregicality exclusive 4 Amps LV energy hatch.

Get §eeither§r of those.

Large Turbines are multiblocks generating a lot of power. They function based on inertia, which means you need to feed them constantly in order for them to reach max output, else they are worthless.

Fuel consumption is 256x bigger than what JEI indicates for LV recipes, or 4x the amount of a HV turbine, regardless of turbine efficiency.
Base power output is 8192eu/t (one IV amp) at 100% efficiency.
Energy efficiency is 4 times as high, assuming 100% efficency.

The Rotor Holder comes in three tiers, HV allows for a max speed of 6000RPM which is default. LuV and MAX rotor holders increase the RPM limit for some more efficiency.

However, the main efficiency comes from the rotor itself. There are 4 tiers of rotor:
Small - Available with Titanium at late HV
Medium - Available with Tungstensteel at late EV
Large - Available with Osmium at IV
Huge - Available with Rutherfordium after fusion in LuV

Materials used in rotors provide different efficiency values. You can only start with small rotors, which sadly means the huge efficiency boost from turbines will be mostly negated.

If you hate oil, glycerol is your only option.

This requires a lot seed/fish oil, and gives Bio Diesel. So that would be part of your power setup.

Allyl Chloride requires Propene, which makes this path require oil processing.
Keep in mind oil processing becomes extremely powerful at EV age with the Distillation Tower giving of §lall§r the hydrocarbons at once.

Propene is also useful for Isoprene, to synthesize Rubber, in case you hate Resin.

Tools using energy to save a lot of durability. Usually one electric tool can last an entire playthrough before it breaks.

The mining drill doubles up as a pickaxe and a shovel. It also has a ridiculous mining speed, it can replace your wrench to mine machines, wires, and such.

The Coke Oven is a staple of the early game in many modpacks.

Use it for Charcoal and Coal Coke.

Refer to JEI for the multiblock shape. The Hatch is an extra access point for input/output that you can use for automation. It will autoouput creosote if there's a connected fluid tank. The Hatch can be placed on any side. Note that you are not limited to one Hatch per Coke Oven.

You may want multiple Coke Ovens, they can share walls.
We are gonna need some §cexplos§rives to generation some §cimplos§rions inside our Implosion Compressor.

"Excuse me Mr. Questbook Writer, why do you include a MV machine in my LV questline!??"

If we were to include a LV Thermal Centrifuge, the best you would be able to do with it would be to use it as a decoration block! The Thermal Centrifuge requires 60eu/t to operate, which means a LV machine cannot process any ore!

This machine is so bad that Gregicality has a config setting to double its output.

With the config off, you're better off centrifuging purified dusts in a regular Centrifuge.

I'll give you a disassembler for your valiant effort to complete this quest. You know what to do.

Eglin steel was developed of use in bunker-buster style munitions.

Its application in the context of large machines is dubious.
Inconel 625 is a nickel-based superalloy made to be corrosion and oxidation-resistant.
Staballoy is an alloy of titanium and uranium, usually in munitions or drilling rods.

Black Bronze... Black Steel... Rose Gold... Why not Blue Steel and Red steel while we're at it? Ah, all of them exist.

While not that useful, these alloys will be required in the future.

If you hate having your Steel GT tools break over and over, make some Blue Steel. Its durability is twice as high.
Maraging Steel 250 is a nickel-cobalt-molybdenum alloy used in high-temperature applications.

Upgrade to the HP boiler as early as possible. It is 2.5 times as fast.

Even with this upgraded version, one boiler won't get you far. Make four of them, or even eight!

Collect large amount of wood using GT axes, keep your coke ovens running and that should be enough charcoal to power all your steam machines as well as your early LV age.

Doing large arrays of solar boilers is also an option... but won't get you far either.

Feeling creative? Want a tool to help you better with multiblocks?

We got you covered! The Freedom Wrench is a great tool with modes that you can cycle with shift right clicking air.

Projection, Pespective, Debug modes help visualize the structure of a multiblock similarly to how MBTweaker.

Building mode is a big time saver! Right click on a multiblock controller and it will automatically place the blocks from your inventory. It will try to reproduce the structure shown by JEI, so you might still have to places hatches yourself, but the wrench still did 90% of the job.


We're not done, shift right click on a controller will rotate it, under any axes. Sideways Electric Blast Furnace, upside down Distillation Tower, you choose! It's a freedom wrench after all.

Talonite is a nickel-chromium alloy usually made into tools.

Talonite apparently is also good for use in industrial machines.

Grisium is a Watertight Steel.

Watertight Steels have properties meant to contain the outwards force upon tank walls created by fluids, as well as to prevent leach into the fluid.

Both the Central Monitor and the Freedom Wrench are an addition from KilaBash.

The Central Monitor is a modular multiblock to display information, images, and remotely access machines from its screens. Going into details on how it works is rather complicated, so we will just say it can do a lot of cool stuff. Check it out sooner than later!

Stellite is a cobalt-chromium alloy designed for wear resistence.

Seeing that you use electrolyzers a lot, maybe this is a fitting application?
No Description
Potin is an alloy used in coins.
Red Steel is an alloy used in I-beams.

Tumbaga is a blanket term for a group of copper-gold alloys.

Stronger than copper, malleable like gold.
The Electromagnetic Separator can get some additional outputs from some ores. Not too important.
<PLACEHOLDER>

Converting MV into LV voltage or vice versa requires a transformer. The default transformer with default configuration takes 1 MV Amp in its input side, and outputs 4 LV Amps on the opposite side (be sure to use 4x cables!). Transforming up is possible but generally less desirable.

Making an electric network and transforming down for LV machines is not recommended in MV, cable loss is still too high. Using single block generators locally is preferred.

Creosote Oil will have its uses, but for now it is worthless and can end up clogging your Coke Oven.

No Extra Utilities in this modpack, but you still have the Universal Bin from NuclearCraft.

If you can't afford this right now and your Coke Oven ends up filled with Creosote, break and replace the block.

Shaping bricks by hand is a little bit of a tricky task! Some kind of mold would help.

Next step is the Coke Oven, you're gonna need 104 Coke Oven Bricks. It is 65 sand and 39 clay.
Gather a lot more clay, it is an essential early game material.

The early game usually tends to be pretty slow in Gregtech. Some modpacks embrace it, some of them skip steps to make it less tedious.

As the goal of the modpack is to provide a full Gregtech + Gregicality experience, all the mechanics are kept. However, we will make it easier on you, with easier recipes and quest rewards. The help will be greater in the early game, and will gradually go away as you progress further. You can also decide to ignore rewards if you wish to be a purist.

Notable modifications for this modpack:
- Circuit recipes give twice as many circuits
- Steam age related recipes are cheaper
- Steel in the Blast Furnace is faster
- Mob loots are not required (also they are disabled in the overworld)


As finding an iron vein may take a little bit of time and mining, we will give a fair deal. Delay mining for later and collect some basic materials instead. Settle down somewhere and we will give you some iron to start off with tools.

These are the other Gregtech tools needed before you reach LV age.

§lWrench:§r
This will end up being your most used tool in the entire modpack. Not only it is a crafting tool, but it is also the preferred tool to mine the machines (please do not use pickaxes!). It doesn't end there, it's also to configure which sides machines are facing, as well as their output configuration.

§lMortar:§r
A crafting tool to grind down some material.

§lScrewdriver:§r
Another crafting tool. Useful as a configuration tool for covers and multiblock controllers, but none of that is happening right now.

§lWire Cutter:§r
Used for the inefficient crafting recipe for wires before you get to the LV age. Can also mine wires, but the wrench does the same job in GTCE.

§lSoft Hammer:§r
A tool to enable/disable when you right click on them. Very useful to save on energy and on steam.

Note: Any material type for these tools will work towards the completion of the quest.

Grind down Copper and Tin using a mortar, combine the dusts in the crafting table, smelt the output and you got yourself some Bronze.

4 Bronze Ingots won't get you far. We recommend you make one stack. Good practice of batch crafting will be a lifesaver.

Completing this quest unlocks the Steam Age.
Better Furnaces might help you through smelting down many ores. Not as important as Omnifactory, as Gregicality has a fancy Steam Oven multiblock available during the steam age.

Crates are similar to chests, but keep their content when broken. Very useful when on mining expeditions.

The tool to mine them is said to be a pickaxe, but a wrench is much faster.

Gregtech has variants the vanilla tools. They are not necessarily worth getting, with the exception of the Axe.

The Axe from Gregtech chops down trees instantly! Who needs OreExcavation?

Axes made out metal require tools to be crafted, but the flint Axe is craftable the vanilla way.

These hammers are excellent for mining, they break blocks in a 3x3 area.

Iron hammers require Gregtech tools to craft.

Diamond hammers require the Forge Hammer available in Steam Age.

Ore Generation is heavily revamped. All vanilla ores are removed in favor of rarer, massive veins containing a few ore types.

When exploring in the world, you'll find traces of ores on the surface, they indicate a specific vein is below them. You can check JEI to see what type of ore veins exist.


While Iron ore, Copper ore and such exist within veins, they are not the only source of these metals. Many ores convert directly into the main metal they are made of. Refer to the Ore Tab to get a listing of the ores.

While not being required right now, you'll be facing off a time gate before the LV age if you don't get ready beforehand. This is due to resistors requiring both paper and resin, and also insulated cables taking both black carpets and strings.

Any seasoned minecraft player would setup a medium sized sugar canes and wheat farm, but let's make sure you do not skip that step!

Once this is done, also setup a Sheep ranch and dye them black. Collect the black wool regularly.


This manual farming won't last long, once settled in LV age you won't need it anymore (I hope you'll let the sheeps free over butchering them...).

Most metals need MV voltage to be melted down using a Fluid Extractor. You can now setup both Fluid Extractor and Fluid Solidifier to shape metals into anything, similarly to the extruder. Alternatively you can use it to recover metal if you crafted it in useless shapes.

You can now make rotors at a 4:1 ratio.

Did you run out of space when automating? Would you wish machines had a additional sides, or rather §bfaces§r?

The Phantomfaces act as an extra access point to the block they are linked to, wirelessly.

You can use them to:
- Avoid having pipes go in all the directions (not too important, EIO conduits help with that already)
- Automate machines, such as the chemical reactor, which need a lot of different inputs and outputs while keeping them organised
- Connect more ME Interfaces to a single machine / input bus so it can handle a lot more than 9 patterns.

Read the Actually Additions book for more details.

If you hate GTCE fluid pipes (like all of us!), you can get EnderIO Pressurized Pluid Conduits.

You can insert/extract fluids in and out of machines by clicking on the corresponding tanks with a fluid container (a bucket will do).
Make Fluid Concrete in the mixer.

By now this is the machine you probably crafted the most as the LV variant. It does not stop there, you will need the HV chemical reactor for various processes.

Despite being more expensive, you might want to consider building full chains with HV chemical reactors when only one recipe requires HV, that way you won't have to transform up or down. Reduce the overclocking on some of your machines to keep a safe energy consumption.

The HV chemical reactor now allows you to get Ammonia directly in one step, from nitrogen and hydrogen. That's of couse only one of many recipes.

Congratulations, you've made some Steel, the main LV material and used extensively throughout the entire modpack.

From now on, keep mass producing Steel, you will need lots of it!

Let's hope your Sheep ranch is going well, cable insulation does indeed require black carpet and string.
You can get string by macerating wool if you're not obtaining them from another source.

The IPBF as a variable size PBF which also enables automation.

The main block - the controller - will only display information. Recipes are done by inserting items in the input bus(es). Steel and dark Ashes will go to the output bus.

Buses auto insert and extract to/from connected inventories on the dot side.
Sticky Resin is obtained from cutting down Rubber Trees, that's why we made included them in an earlier quest!

Paper is a little bit trickier to obtain and the ratio of sugar canes -> paper is considerably worse. You got that sugar cane farm going don't you?

At LV, you will be able to obtain paper much more efficiently, simply from wood if you wish to.

Bronze Pipes will be the first way you can transfer steam aroun, they are also used in crafting recipes.

GTCE fluid pipes are really mediocre, consider switching them to EIO fluid conduits as soon as possible.
The base of all circuits is the Circuit Board! These Boards require preparation to be used, and this one uses 8 copper wires.

The Forge Hammer is an extremely helpful early game machine.

It can perform most of the recipes that normally are done in the crafting table with a Hammer (Hammer + item).
It can make plates at a 3:2 ratio.
It can make gears more efficiently, amongst some other things.

Wrought Iron was the most common form of malleable iron before widespread and efficient steel production came around.

Wrought Iron can be used for tools, and has 1.5x base durability.
Smelt Iron Ingots in a furnace to make hot Iron, and hammer it in a crafting table. No mittens needed, Steve is fairly heat-proof.

Don't turn all of your iron into wrought iron! You cannot convert it back, and they are both used.
Resistors reduce the voltage across them in an electric circuit.

Congratulations! You've completed the Steam Age, its time for electric machines and the Age of LV.

Make a few of these circuits for the time being. They will become significantly easier to make as you progress throughout LV.

Make both the LV machine hull and LV Electric Motor to get yourself started in LV. Less detailed help on how to obtain them!

The Steam Mixer is a steam machine that mixes items and fluids into a single fluid.

Recipes in JEI display eu/t which refers to electric machines. Steam machines can perform these recipes up to 32eu/t.

§lImportant note: The Mixer does not have an item output and will void whatever you are attempting to craft it is not a fluid!§r
This machine can compress various materials. It can turn ingots into blocks, as well as some materials into plates.

The Steam Grinder is the multiblock version of the steam macerator.

I utilizes more steam to macerate 8 items at once per recipe. This machine has utility up to HV age, or beyond.

Note: Same as the Steam Oven, this multiblock is expensive and should be built during the LV age instead.

The Macerator, so well known essential machine for ore doubling, no different in here! However... Ore processing can get in the way, let's take a little bit of time explaining how it goes in the simple details.

Smelting: 1 ore -> 1 ingot, unchanged
Macerating: 1 ore -> 2 ingots, unchanged

Crushed Ores are the first step of ore processing, which is out of the scope of this little introduction. The main thing you need to know is that 1 crushed ore equals to 1 standard dust. You will have to hammer down the crushed ore to an impure dust, this is done either by using a Hammer tool in the crafting table, or using the Steam Forge Hammer. Then, you throw the impure dust in a vanilla cauldron filled with water, this will clean the dust and turn it into a regular dust. This last step is not necessary for metals.

You can smelt impure and regular dusts in furnaces to get the metal. Ores made partially of metals (Limonite, Chalcopyrite...) will give nuggets instead.


§lNote: Macerating, hammering, and then smelting (sometimes into nuggets) is really slow! Consider what you want between time efficiency and ore efficiency. You can always mine more ores to make up for poorer ore processing.

Steam Multiblock Furnace! This machine smelts 8 items at a time.

A really efficient way to smelt a lot of materials, will last a while even after you progress into electric ages.
Consult JEI to form the multiblock.

Note: This multiblock is expensive in steam age, we recommend getting it only once settle in LV age.

Your main component in MV age.

The cheaper recipe is available only after you get the MV assembler.

Many questions arise regarding the EBF, and Gregtech multiblocks in general.
The most common is: "Why is my EBF not working?".

First, make sure the multiblock is assembled correctly. You can shift right click the controller with an empty hand. If a block appears red, it means you placed something that should not be there. If the controller itself is red, it means you are not meeting the requirement for hatches/buses or minimum casings. Check the JEI preview to figure out what you need. Not all machines are hollow.

Multiblocks hate chunk borders, this can result in causing them to load incorrectly. Always keep the entire structure of a multiblock in a single chunk.

Any tier of bus/hatches will work to assemble most multiblocks. But you always need to make sure it has space to output the items, or it will simply not operate. If the EBF has a fluid recipe, be sure to add Fluid Hatches.

Lastly, it may not work because of the energy requirement. Be sure the recipe you want to run fits within the max eu/t mentionned in the controller GUI. Tin cables have energy transfer loss!! Be sure to stick your generators and/or battery buffer as close to your EBF as possible!!

The same applies to every voltage tier, you will need these components.

We also added Sensor and Emitter, enjoy!
As the tier goes up, the tier of glass also does. You will now need Reinforced Glass in machine recipes.

You may notice we do not include all the steps anymore. We will restrict ourselves to only display important intermediates, and the final product you need to aim for. This will reduce the amount of fluid you have to submit, because there are lot of them! It also teaches you how to use JEI, I hope you have figured that one out already.

Copper cables! Your first insulation material for MV cables is Polycaprolactam. Later comes Polyethylene.

Saltpeter can be obtained from electrolyzing Niter. Polycaprolactam has to be made as a fluid and then solidified.

It is also known as Nylon-6.

The Electric Blast Furnace heating coils will require some insulation.

You can choose from Alumino-Silicate Wool or Mica Insulator Foil. It is recommended you use Mica, especially in the future. Both paths require Silicon Dioxide, its best source is glass dust in a centrifuge.

You will need 196 Alumino Silicate Wool or 128 Mica Insulator Foil for one EBF. Always a good thing to be prepared!

While the Large Bronze Boiler is not required, it is heavily recommended! It is capable of outputting large quantities of steam unlike small boilers.

Just like small boilers, the large boiler will not stop simply because your steam isnt being consumed. It will also blow up if it doesnt have water and you add some when it's already hot!

At full power, it can run 14 LV steam turbines.
At full throttle, it can run 1.4 LV steam turbines.

We recommend throtlling it, else you won't be able to keep up with the fuel consumption. Creosote can be burned in it, so you can also stop voiding the semifluid.

Combustion type fuels also work in the boiler, however they last 2x less than the duration shown in JEI in the boiler. Semifluid Fuels last 2x as long as shown in JEI. You can also burn furnace fuels.

You may have noticed Oil Wells across the world. Now it is time to tackle them.

While most Oil products can be interchanged with biological versions, you still need to start off with it.

Oil comes in varietes:§
§

§6Oil§r - plain, regular oil, you will most likely want this one
§6Light oil§r - richer in refinery gas
§6Raw Oil§r - same as regular oil, but less dense
§6Heavy oil§r - richer in heavy fuel, requires MV to process

Light Fuel and Diesel are an alternative for power, but are not required.

The scrict minimum required oil to progress for now is one of the following amounts: Oil - 30B, Raw Oil - 60B, or Light Oil - 90B.

You can also use a GT pump to harvest oil, but you'll need a connected energy source to power it. The Steam Pump is a potential alternative.
You can now process many more dusts from ores. No more pesky smelting limonite dusts giving off nuggets, eww!

Putting large batches of dusts in the Electrolyzer is a bit tedious. You need to do some math and put exact amount of dusts to avoid clogging it up.

Let's fix that issue, shall we? This is a small guide on how to automate the Electrolyzer.


The robot arm is extremely powerful, it allows you to insert/extract items at specific rates.
Put a filter on it, and you can regulate rates for said filtered items.
Put a smart filter on it, and it will regulate *all* the electrolyzable dusts, with no effort!


Now this isn't the end, electrolyzing dusts gives off "fluids". Water, Oxygen, Hydrogen, Chlorine and Fluorine.
Void water, and have a tank dedicated to all other outputs. Oxygen and Hydrogen can also be voided (not recommended). §lDo not ever void Chlorine or Fluorine, they will be important.§r

Gallium's best friend! You can't obtain it directly from an ore, and you need it for circuits.

Get it from electrolyzing cobaltite or other dusts. Some means require the MV Electrolyzer.

This is the first major crafting component. Prepare to make many. Remember to batch-craft if you don't want to end up like Kharax82 and his endless GT:NH playthrough.

You will first need to produce power. This comes in the form of steam at the beginning, so make a steam turbine or four!

Polyethylene (PE), the most common plastic used in the world, will also be the most commonly used plastic in Gregtech.

Getting it will require a little bit of chemistry. Nothing too bad, I promise.


Polyethylene can be obtained from 2 different methods. One comes from wood/charcoal, and the other comes from oil. Both require quite a few steps, but chemicals you're making along the way will also have other purposes.

This is the first instance of a divergence which will dictate your playstyle, perhaps even up to LuV! Do not worry not, we'll guide you through both, you won't always have this luxury!

This is the oil processing path. Right now it is less recommended due to the inability to reliably to gather large amount of oil during the MV age.
Once you reach EV, this path will be heavily preferred, and eventually required.

Remember the Naphtha processing? Well, it's the same, except for Light Fuel for higher yield.

Light Fuel is also usable for power, and can be mixed with Heavy Fuel to make Diesel for even more power.

You can start off oil cracking in a MV Chemical Reactor. This process will be better with the Oil Cracking Unit in HV.

Steam crack Light Fuel, then distill it into Ethylene. This process will also be better in EV with the Distillation Tower, allowing you to get all the hydrocarbons instead of just one.

This is Step 1 of the Platinum Process.

The Platinum process is complicated and takes up a lot of space. Build dedicated machines for each step.

Sift the Platinum Salt into Refined Platinum Salt, then run it through a blast furnace to get back some Platinum Metallic Powder. Build dedicated blast furnaces for this process. The Large Sifter gets you significantly more out of your platinum this way, since it actually increases the sifting chance to 100%.
React the Recipricated Platinum Dust with Calcium, to produce platinum!

This is the start of the Palladium Process. There are two ways to approach this. Split your palladium metallic powder supply in half, react half with ammonia, and react the Palladium enriched ammonia with the other palladium metallic powder. Or, you can devote all your metallic powder to the palladium enriched ammonia from the platinum process.

The Palladium Salt can be sifted the same as the Platinum Salt, and processed back into Palladium Metallic Powder, without the blast furnace step.
This is the final step in the Palladium Process
This is the beginning of the Rhodium and Residue processes.

Electrolyze the zinc sulfate.

Blast furnace the crude rhodium metal into rhodium salt.

The next steps in the Rhodium process.

Sift the rhodium nitrate in the large sifter into rhodium filter cake.
Rhodium is important for Rhodium Plated Palladium, which is the LuV base material.
This is the first step of the Ruthenium Process.
No Description
You won't need this until LuV, but it doesn't hurt to process it now.
This is the first method of obtaining Iridium. Better methods will be available later, but you should still process it this way too.
Centrifuge the Sludge Residue.
Centrifuge the metallic sludge dust. Iridium is an important material, it will be used more prominantly at later times.
You can now build Field Generators, which unlocks many new machines. You also can build Larger Super/Quantum Tanks and Chests, change your oil processing buffers to them!

You will need either Sodium Bisulfate or Iron III Chloride for circuit boards.
Iron III Chloride is recommended.

Get §eeither§r to complete the quest... or hit the checkbox if you want to use 4 times as much copper for your MV boards. That option won't be available for future circuit boards.
Use either Scheelite or Tungstate dust, first available from Mars, to make Sodium Tungstate. This is the beginning of the Tungsten Process.
Can also be used to make Tungstensteel, which is the IV base material.
Has some specific use-cases.

Oil can be distilled into Light Fuel, Heavy Fuel, Naphtha and Refinery Gas.

What you want right now is Naphtha, this will be your first source of MV cable insulation.

If you're still struggling with JEI, here's a tip: Oil in distillery can give you Sulfuric Naphtha (be sure to use the correct configuration circuit!), which can be refined to regular Naphtha in the chemical reactor using hydrogen.

Hydrogen Sulfide can be recycled back to Hydrogen in a closed loop, giving off a sulfur byproduct. This is not important right now, but will become crucial when refining oil in the future.

DO THIS FIRST!!!

This machine makes wires at a 1:2 ratio.
Also makes fine wires from wires at a 1:4 ratio.

A small note about overclocking: click on the button defaulting to [LV] and change it either to [ULV] or [OFF]. This will prevent this machine from consuming 32eu/t instead of 8eu/t as stated by JEI. Overclocking will be explained in more details once you reach MV.

Gregtech has a lot of fluids, a lot!

Tanks are very handy as they can fill or empty the machine internal tanks from the GUI itself.

GregTech Tanks or Drums are good as mentioned from before, as well as EnderIO tanks which can be used to extract fluids from machines in world as well as in the GUI.

All of them store content when broken.

Get §eany§r of these tanks to complete this quest.
Did somebody say massive chest? Bring me on board!

Sodium, Cadmium and Lithium all require slightly advanced ore processing to be obtained. We recommend centrifuging chalcopyrite for cadmium as it makes the best batteries.

Batteries can fit inside the energy slot of machines. Buffering energy is something you will want to do in quite a few circumstances.

Get §eany§r battery to complete this quest.

You will never guess what this alloy is for.

Antimony mainly comes from Stibnite ore.

Putting a battery inside every single machine is quite impractical. Furthermore, multiblocks do not accept them.

Battery buffers exist in multiple forms, 1 slot, 4 slots, 9 slots, 16 slots. Most of the time, 4 slots is the sweet spot.

Keep in mind: Battery buffers output multiple Amps of power, so you §cwill§r need to use cables that support amps equal to or greater than the amount of batteries in your buffer, else they will burn.

This is the first LV power-producing machine.

Power should be transported using tin cables. Always use insulated cables unless you are feeling like getting electrocuted.

You will need more LV turbines later on, but one is good to get you started.

Through the steam age, you have been dealing with crushed ores, and you didnt want them! All you wanted was either clean dusts or ingots. Their purpose is to enhance ore processing, and give §9byproducts§r.

Not many ores are worth processing for side products. It is rather slow and power hungry. You will however need to do it to get materials which do not exist as an ore variant, and there are many of them. Feel free to consult JEI ore byproduct tab do determine if an ore is worth processing.

Before moving on, we heavily recommend setting all 4 machines above this quest as they greatly improve the material conversion rate to intermediates.

Your next main step should be the assembling machine, but you won't be able to craft it directly.

End goals of LV age are the Electric Blast Furnace for Aluminium, and the Primitive Assembly circuit.

It may be abundant in the air, but collecting it takes a little bit of processing.

Many, many and many more chemical processes will require oxygen, it is best you store oxygen in a tank, and later automate it.

There are two ways to produce oxygen: Centrifuge Air or Electrolyze Water.

Air is faster and cheaper energy wise, but requires an extra machine to collect: The Air Collector.

Making hydrogen is a little power hungry right now. But you'll need a decent amount of it.

Similar to oxygen, you will need a lot of it. Store it in a tank, and automate it later.
While Annealed Copper can be made in the Blast Furnace, the Arc Furnace recipe is much better. You will need this material in MV.

They are truly amazing.

They don't require ender pearls in this modpack.

Gold Ore has been mostly replaced with Precious Metal Ore in Gregicality.

You can smelt it directly into gold nuggets, but the yield is abysmal.

Precious Metal has 4 steps of processing. Each step has a recovery process, granting more and more gold. The final step also grants iron, nickel, lead and silver byproducts.

You will need Nitric Acid and Hydrochloric Acid for the full chain. You don't need to setup a full processing chain for them, use JEI to figure out a way to recycle the byproducts back into Nitric Acid and Hydrochloric Acid. Closed loops chemical processing will be a recurrent theme.

Now that you have unlocked cheaper components, it is time to fully embrace crafting in batches.

This will make your life much easier, severely reducing the amount of microcrafting when getting a new machine. Use the assembler whenever you can.

Put your rubber trees to good use! Hopefully you made the centrifuge already and got yourself some rubber pulp. You can now use the chemical reactor to make molten rubber, and solidify it into sheets. This is needed to unlock the conveyor module and the Assembling Machine.

Rubber Foil is also a much better insulation material to use for wires than carpets.
Ender IO Farming Station is going to be your only option for an automated tree farm. This will become mandatory for wood based power sources.

Another important component.

It has no uses other than crafting.

This machine makes plates at a 1:1 ratio.

It also can make Foils, dense Plates, and more.

This machine lets you make Rods at a 1:2 ratio. Even though it isn't direct (available at MV), it is significantly better than filing for rods.
It also makes Screws from Bolts at a 1:1 ratio.
This machine magnetizes materials without needing redstone. It is required to magnetize steel rods.

Centrifuges spin materials around and use centripetal force to separate them.

The Centrifuge has a lot of uses! For ore processing, it turns impure/purified dusts into regular dusts, giving off byproducts. Always try to use the Centrifuge over the Ore Washer, it is more energy efficient.

This machine is the first step in producing Liquid Rubber. Centrifuge the Rubber item into Raw Rubber Pulp, and other materials. You could also use an extractor, but centrifuging also yields Glue, which is useful in combination with the Assembling Machine.

You will build lots and lots of chemical reactors. This is your all-purpose fluid processing machine.

Do not build this as your first machine.

Another component.

It can be used as a cover to import or export fluids, and can also be filtered. Configure it by RClicking with a screwdriver in hand.

It does what it sounds like.

In conjuction with the chemical reactor, you can mow make rubber.

Electrolyzes materials using electricity to separate them.

The final step of ore processing will often require electrolysis, though that is mostly MV.
It puts items into items, simple enough? It is needed for batteries.

Another component.

This can be used as a cover to move items. It supports all the advanced item transfer features.

Another Component

This can also be used as a configurable cover for moving items. It cannot use more advanced item transfer features, like only allowing a certain amount of items in an inventory.

This machine allows you to make all of the components for much cheaper. This machine is a priority for every voltage tier. Also note that many parts of the primitive circuits are now much cheaper with this machine.

The chemical bath has a similar purpose as the Ore Washer, except it uses Sodium Persulfate or Mercury to have a great chance of obtaining secondary output. It rarelly is worth it.

Right now, the chemical bath can also be used to make paper from wood dust.
The forming press is a niche machine. One of the paths to the first EBF coils requires it.
This machine can turn gem dusts into gems, among other things.

The Sifter is typically used to recover gems from crushed ores, else you would simply obtain dusts.

This will become important later on.
The steam mixer does not have an item output, so you will need this at some point. Also used for Mica foils for the EBF.

These components are upgraded versions of the basic resistors, diodes, transistors and diodes.

It is advised to use the highest tier of SMD components whenever you can, as you trade resource cost for complexity.

Always craft them in batches of several stacks (except for the diodes, they are used less).

This is the last batch craft quest for you, as the Incredible Bulk 3 was never announced. Good practice gives good rewards.

You might not need to batch craft things in HV anymore if you start mass automating with Applied Energistics.
This material can only be made in the Alloy Blast Furnace.
Polyvinyl Chloride (PVC) is another common polymer. It has fewer uses overall.

I hope your first batch of Polycaprolactam lasted long enough to get here.

You can now insulate cables through MV to EV using Polyethylene foils. While not being strictly cheaper, it is a lot more convenient.

Overclocking happens when the EU/t cost of a recipe is within a lower voltage than the machine handling it. The machine will consume four times as much power, and process the recipe faster. There is a catch though, you lose energy efficiency.

Remember the case with the LV Wiremill? Wires recipe costs were 8eu/t, and are overclocked to 32eu/t.
With a MV Wiremill, the recipe would be overclocked once more, consuming 128eu/t to fit the current voltage tier.

The speed boost depends on the base cost of the recipe:
- 16EU/t and less: 2x speed boost (net 2x energy cost per overclock)
- between 17EU/t and 32EU/t: 2.8x speed boost (net 1.42x energy cost per overclock)
All LV machines will require this.

It washes ores into clean versions.

Important notice: you can obtain purified ores without this machine by throwing crushed ores in a cauldron!

The Arc Furnace uses oxygen. It can recycle many things.

It is very handy to create Wrought Iron directly, and make Annealed Copper.

This is just the beginning of making alloys.

2 stacks of cupronickel will be required to craft the coils for the Electric Blast Furnace.

And roughly 1 stack of Invar for the casings.

Extracts fluids from items.

Use in combination with the assembler to craft many things.

These coils will be used in the Electric Blast Furnace. They also have other uses.

In the blast furnace, coil tier dictates what recipes can be run. A recipe that exceeds the temperature of the coils cannot be run in the blast furnace. Higher temperature coils do not speed up the machine, and only allow it to run new recipes. You can speed up the EBF with higher voltage.

You have created the Electric Blast Furnace! A true magic box which can... Wait no, wrong mod. The EBF is a multiblock, and it is also very power hungry! If you want to avoid having power issues, be sure to have batteries ready (check that quest out).

The first thing you will make with this machine is Aluminium.

It also produces steel granted you have enough oxygen, making the Primitive Blast Furnace obsolete.

Steel was the main LV material. Aluminium is the main MV material.

Ramp up your power production as early as possible, so you can run your EBF without interruption. You will need a lot of aluminium.
Use Pure Thorium fuel directly into waste.

Gallium will be important throughout the game. It is used to make diodes for right now.

There is no gallium ore, you have to obtain it through Sphalerite ore processing.

These basic diodes will eventually be phased out.

Note: Naquadah and Enriched Naquadah have centrifuging recipes to make Naquadria. Naquadria can be Large Centrifuged into many useful materials, like Lutetium and Pu244.

Naquadah Reactors are great sources of power. Note the complex fuel process, and the useful products made from Complicated Naquadah Gas and Enriched Naquadah Solution. Naquadah Gas is also a very good fuel source for Gas power.

Gregtech tools can be made out of many materials. The material mostly determines durability and mining speed, with sometimes a bonus enchantment. For example weapons made out flint will have Fire Aspect, useful to cook food instantly when hunting animals.

Another crafting tool. You can also use it to get more planks from wood.

The Primitive Blast Furnace, commonly referred as the PBF or BBF, is a multiblock capable of forming Steel from Iron and Coal/Charcoal.

You may know of other Blast Furnaces from other mods, but do worry not. In this modpack, Steel takes 12.5 seconds from Iron, and only 5 seconds from Wrought Iron.

Start from 132 clay, then split them equally (66 each) between clay dust and clay bricks. Combine the dusts into Fireclay which is your insulation material for your PBF.

Consult JEI for the formation of the multiblock.

This machine can produce various Coal products on top of doubling up as a Coke Oven. Both are good for fuel. Additionally, Wood Vinegar is very useful for various chemicals, and Fermented Biomass is a good source of Ethanol.

Making Wood Tar, and distilling it into Benzene for use in Gas Turbines is also very advisable.

More coils needed? Yes, batch craft a lot of Mica Insulation for future Coils as well. The Pyrolyse Oven accepts better coils to speed up the recipes.

Despite there being 4 methods of getting Ethanol, we recommend getting it from Fermented Biomass made in the Pyrolyse Oven.

Mix Ethanol and Sulfuric Acid to get Ethylene.

Ethylene can also be obtained from distilling Wood Gas, which also comes from the Pyrolyse Oven. The poor yield makes it a lot less recommendable.

Get §eeither§r Ethanol or Wood Gas to complete this quest.


An additional note about Ethanol: If you are mass producing it, you can consider mixing it with seed/fish oil for Bio Diesel, a good alternative for power which can be further refined into Nitro Diesel. It also gives Glycerol byproduct which is rather useful.

Converts any voltage to any other voltage using energy hatches over chaining multiple transformer blocks.

HV Power Suggestion:
1. 8 Oil->Sulfuric Heavy Fuel LV Distilleries
   12 Oil->Sulfuric Light Fuel LV Distilleries

2. 2 LV Chemical reacotrs for desulfurification, 3 LV electrolyzers for hydrogen sulfide

3. 1 MV mixer for diesel

4. Power everything with diesel generators, transform down MV generators for the distilleries.

The above setup produces enough diesel for about 7 HV diesel generators and have fuel gain. It produces barely less than enough to run 8 diesel generators, equivalent to 1 Large Combustion Engine (EV) and 3 HV diesel gens.

The HV macerator finally unlocks all 3 slots, allowing you to get significantly more byproducts from ores. A must have in any ore processing chain.

We will tell you to the last thing to know about overlocking: the % bonus indicated per tier is applied for each overclock. Overclock once, and you get that bonus indicated. Overclock twice, and you get that bonus twice!

Needless to say, the EV macerator will be a good upgrade once you get there.

This machine is a better version of the chemical reactor. One of its benefits is that it can process multiple different recipes much easier. 

A good example of this is when doing oil processing. You can have one hydrogen input be accessable for all 4 oil distillation products, and process all of them simulaneously.

The following is the main route to Plutonium 244, an important material for the next circuit tiers. You will also be able to create Pu244 through Naquadria or fusion later on.

When it comes to making nuclear products, it is best to use the most common isotope wherever possible: U238, Np237, Pu244, Am243, Cm250, Bk249, Cf252, Es255, Fm258, and Md261.
Process Plutonium and run it through the nuclear process to make Pu244, and processing the depleted fuel.

There are 2 main options for Acetone:

Option 1 - Distill Wood Vinegar (from pyrolyse).

Option 2 - Make Acetic Acid first, then react with Calcium (or a composite with Calcium, such as Calcite or Quicklime) for Calcium Acetate Solution. Distill or heat that up for Acetone. Using a Distillation Tower for the last step gives back Quicklime.

Option 3 - As a byproduct from making Phenol from Cumene (check that quest out). Note that you need 2 Acetote per Phenol, so this is not ideally used as the sole source.

Option 5 - React Benzene and Oxygen (this requires an EV chemical reactor)
